      <p>When most people think of corrugated cardboard sheets, they picture the outer walls of a shipping box. But experienced packers and logistics professionals across Malaysia know that corrugated sheets have a second life as versatile inner packaging components — particularly as layer pads, dividers, and corner protectors. This application is especially valuable for furniture manufacturers and electronics exporters in Selangor who need reliable, low-cost protection inside their cartons.</p>

      <p>Quinocycle Sdn. Bhd. in Balakong supplies corrugated cardboard sheets to a wide range of industries. This guide focuses specifically on how to use sheets for internal packaging protection.</p>

      <h2 class="font-headline text-2xl font-bold text-on-surface mt-10 mb-4">What Are Corrugated Layer Pads?</h2>
      <p>A layer pad is simply a flat corrugated sheet cut to the internal dimensions of a carton or pallet. When placed between tiers of products in a box or on a pallet, it distributes the weight of the upper layer evenly across the lower items — preventing point-load crushing, which is a leading cause of damage in stacked shipments.</p>

      <h3 class="font-headline text-xl font-semibold text-on-surface mt-6 mb-3">When to Use Layer Pads</h3>
      <p>Layer pads are essential when stacking fragile items like ceramic tiles, glassware, packaged electronics, or flat-pack furniture pieces inside a master carton or on export pallets. The pad acts as a rigid intermediary layer that maintains safe stacking pressure. Without them, items at the bottom of a stack bear the full concentrated weight of everything above — often beyond the manufacturer's safe load rating.</p>

      <h3 class="font-headline text-xl font-semibold text-on-surface mt-6 mb-3">Choosing the Right Thickness</h3>
      <p>For light goods (up to 3 kg per layer), single wall (3-ply) corrugated sheets at 3–4mm are sufficient. For heavier goods — furniture boards, machine parts, packed bottles — double wall (5-ply) sheets at 6–8mm provide better compressive strength and are less likely to bow under load. The right choice depends on your product weight and how many layers you stack.</p>

      <h2 class="font-headline text-2xl font-bold text-on-surface mt-10 mb-4">Corrugated Sheets as Inner Box Dividers</h2>
      <p>Box dividers are corrugated sheets cut and interlocked to create a grid of individual cells inside a larger carton. Each product goes into its own cell, preventing item-to-item contact that causes scratching, chipping, and breakage. This is a low-cost alternative to custom moulded foam inserts.</p>

